description:
After hatching, many  birds remove eggshells from the nest.  Unlike other birds, about 40% of American Avocets don't just fly a short distance and drop the shells.  Instead, they carry it some distance from their nest, and swirl it around in the water, as if washing the eggshell, and then drop it in deep water away from their nest.

A detailed description of Avocet eggshell removal behavior can be found here: https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/jfo/v065n04/p0461-p0465.pdf

It seems to have some prey - notice the wing sticking out.

Green Sharp Shooter (Draeculacephala minerva) was from a population Rodrigo Almeida at UC Berkeley maintained and the original population came from from insects that were wild-caught in and around Berkeley, CA. The sharp shooter was dissected to remove the bacteriome and then I gently smashed the bacteriome on a slide to release the symbionts. Single bacterial cells were captured with a micromanipulator on an inverted scope. Sulcia cells were amplified and we recovered a full genome back form a single bacterial cell. 
http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0010314

description: Collin spotted this one, thereby adding another Triteleia to my life list. My key distinguishes this from T. ixioides (which I've seen in the Sierra but which apparently grows in the Coast Ranges as well) based on color (boo), tube length (double boo), and the shape of the filaments, which should be "lobed" in T. ixioides and unlobed in T. lugens. Looking at my photo, the filaments looked pretty lobed to me, until I did some photo comparisons and realized that the lobes on T. ixioides are big projections, not just rounded edges like I was thinking. Pictures: 1. Words: 0.

description:
For the longest time people would ask me what the weird orange stuff growing in marshes was and I'd say I thought it was some weird algae.  No idea where I got that notion, but it's totally wrong: it's dodder!  Dodder is a strange, rootless, fully-parasitic vine that penetrates the stems of its host, much like mistletoe.  This species actually isn't the marsh one, but an upland cousin.

As I was looking at these flowers, I couldn't quite tell if they belonged to the dodder or the host (which may have been a buckwheat).  Now I know.  And knowing is half the battle.  G.I. Joe.

description: Condors are a bit mythic, the kind of birds you see on TV nature documentaries growing up but never actually expect to see in person.  And when you get to visit a place where such creatures supposedly exist, it's always a question whether or not you'll encounter them, and if you do, whether your encounter will be through a cage, among a crowd, listening to a ranger explain what you're seeing.  Well, I'm happy to report that California Condors are both real and easily encounterable on your own at Pinnacles.  From a distance they were a bit hard to distinguish from Turkey Vultures (the splayed primaries help), but when you get up close and see the white markings, they're unmistakeable.  Amazing birds.
Streptanthus glandulosus is my 3rd flower observed in this genus, and further cements my affection for the lot of them.
